 You have been warned.
@endnode

@node Install "Requirements & Installation"

 Requirements
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~
  Kickstart 2.0 or above, normal disk drives (i.e. those under the control
 of the system's own trackdisk.device), and at least a sketchy knowledge of
 what you're doing if you intend to use any of the options other then those
 associated with @{" drive click " link Usage 79}.

 Installation
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~
  DrivePrefs is a CLI command, so put it in your C: directory, then just
 use it in your startup-sequence or whatever. If you use the @{" NOCLICK " link Usage 79} and
 @{" SEEKZERO " link Usage 89} options (see @{" Usage " link Usage}), you can put it right at the beginning
 of your startup and never have to hear a single click ever again!
@endnode

@node Usage

 Usage
 ~~~~~
 DrivePrefs may be used from the shell or a script file. It is also a pure
command, and so may be made resident. The following options are available:

 DrivePrefs @{"Units" link Usage 31"} @{"S=STEP n" link Usage 45} @{"T=SETTLE n" link Usage 58} @{"C=CALIBRATE n" link Usage 63} @{"R=RETRY" link Usage 68}
            @{"CL=CLICK" link Usage 83} @{"NC=NOCLICK" link Usage 79} @{"TC=TOGGLECLICK" link Usage 86} @{"SZ=SEEKZERO" link Usage 89}

 Options such as T=SETTLE mean that SETTLE is the normal keyword, but may be
abbreviated to T, so that:
  @{i}DrivePrefs S=2200 T=11000 NC SZ@{ui}
is the same as:
  @{i}DrivePrefs STEP=2200 SETTLE=11000 NOCLICK SEEKZERO@{ui}
or even:
  @{i}DrivePrefs S 2200 SETTLE 11000 NC SEEKZERO@{ui}
...you get the idea. (If you don't, just forget about this program, please.)

If you really can't be bothered reading this, I use the program like this:

  Run <>NIL: DrivePrefs S=2129 T=10641 C=2838 R=1 NC SZ

 (Using the Run command saves a couple of milliseconds when using
@{" SEEKZERO " link Usage 89}, by allowing startup to continue while DrivePrefs waits for the
drive heads to step. Using Run is not necessary, by any means.)
 However, be sure to read the @{" DIRE WARNINGS " link Usage 111} below. Some of these options
can be dangerous, and timings should not be changed if you really don't know
what you're doing.

Explanation of options:

<units>:
  Specify which drives to operate on by their number, i.e. 0 for DF0:,
 1 for DF1:, etc., e.g.

   DrivePrefs 0 3 <options...>

  This will change the settings on DF0: and DF3:, without changing the
 configuration of any other drives.

  If no units are specified, @{b}ALL@{ub} connected drives, from DF0: to DF3: will
 be affected, e.g.

 DrivePrefs <options...>

@{b}S@{ub}TEP (abbreviation S):
 Change the delay between stepping the heads to the given value, in
ticks of the system 'E Clock', roughly equivalent to microseconds. This
can be used to reduce the amount of noise the drive makes, but will not
significantly speed up access. Trackdisk's own default value is 3000.
See @{" Calculating Timings " link Timings} and @{" DIRE WARNINGS " link Usage 111} below. (These timing options
will not change anything if they are not specified in the command line.)

Example: DrivePrefs 0 STEP 2129
          - set step delay on DF0: to 3 milliseconds
         DrivePrefs 2 S=3000
          - set DF2's step delay to the default value

SE@{b}T@{ub}TLE (abbreviation T):
 Change the delay after stepping the heads (head settle delay) to the given
value in E Clock ticks. Trackdisk's own default value is 15000.
See @{" Calculating Timings " link Timings} and @{" DIRE WARNINGS " link Usage 111} below.

@{b}C@{ub}ALIBRATE (abbreviation C):
 Change the calibrate delay for the specified drives to the given
value in E Clock ticks. Trackdisk's own default value is 4000.
See @{" Calculating Timings " link Timings} and @{" DIRE WARNINGS " link Usage 111} below.

@{b}R@{ub}ETRY (abbreviation R):
 Change the number of retries the system will make on a damaged track to
the given value, e.g. 0 will cause a read/write error requester to appear
immediately when a track is read in wrongly, 3 will result in a total of
4 attempts before giving a requester. The system default value is 10, and
the maximum possible is 255.
 Setting this to a high value can help when trying to read from a damaged
disk. Setting it to a low value (I use 1) will give an early warning of
damaged disks. Useful if, like mine, they are mostly over 5 years old and
starting to turn back into oil.

@{b}N@{ub}O@{b}C@{ub}LICK (abbreviation NC)
 Turns off drive click on the specified drives. The @{" SEEKZERO " link Usage 89} option
is very useful in conjunction with this. Also see @{" DIRE WARNINGS " link Usage 111} below.

@{b}CL@{ub}ICK (abbreviation CL)
 Turns drive click back on again :)

@{b}T@{ub}OGGLE@{b}C@{ub}LICK (abbreviation TC)
 Toggles drive click.

@{b}S@{ub}EEK@{b}Z@{ub}ERO (abbreviation SZ)
 This option moves the heads to track zero in all empty drives, shutting
them up immediately when used with @{" NOCLICK " link Usage 79} (it can also be used without
this, but just makes a stupid noise :), so that you can put it at the
beginning of your startup-sequence for a silent bootup!
 Why move the heads all the way back to track zero? Well, it is useful due
to the way in which the Amiga checks for disks. The system is informed
immediately when a disk is removed from the drive, but has to step the heads
in order to detect when one has been reinserted. This is why Amiga drives
click when there are no disks in them.
 Now, normally it will move the heads in one direction during one
click, then move them in the opposite direction next time. When the
TDUF_NOCLICK flag is set (this is the way all anti-click utilities work),
the heads are only ever stepped in one direction, towards track zero. When
they get there, they can't step out any more, and the click stops (This can
be problematic. See @{" DIRE WARNINGS " link Usage 111} below.), which is fine, but if the
heads aren't at track zero, the drives  can't be shut up for a good 10
seconds or so. This happens when booting from HD with empty drives, so that
the drives can't stop clicking for some time, often continuing to click
until after Workbench has loaded.


 @{b}DIRE WARNINGS@{ub}
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 This command allows you to tinker with some fairly low-level timings and
suchlike. While it does do this in a perfectly system-friendly way, you
should be aware that you can mess things up.

 Firstly, DrivePrefs' @{" NOCLICK " link Usage 79} option (like any similar utility), sets
the NOCLICK flag in the relevant system structures, which causes the drives
to attempt to move the heads outwards from the outermost track. Newer drives
just ignore this command (but will still update the disk changed flag as
normal), but older ones just step them out anyway, bashing them off the end
stop. I AM PRETTY SURE THIS WAS AT LEAST PARTLY RESPONSIBLE FOR SLOWLY
BREAKING MY LAST INTERNAL DRIVE. (This was before I wrote DrivePrefs, but
the program I used did the same thing.) So, if when using the @{" NOCLICK " link Usage 79}
option, you can still hear a faint click (it's more of a putt...putt than a
clack...clack), you would be advised not to use this option, or any similar
utility (then again, maybe the drive's not important to you, and you just
want it to shut up :).

 Right, now the drive timing settings. If you change these, be sure that
you have some idea of what you're doing. Trying to operate your drives
outside their specifications (see @{" Calculating Timings " link Timings} if you want to use
values based on your drive specification) is a somewhat dodgy enterprise.
Giving time delays which are too long won't do any harm (it'll just make
your drives sound terrible), but if you try to make them go too fast, then
reading the disk will produce frequent read errors. These aren't "real", and
will go away when you put the timings back. Any write errors which pop up,
however, will of course be a little more permanent... Lowering the delay
settings will give you quieter drives, but just be  careful, OK? Timings can
vary between drive models and manufacturers.

 The @{" RETRY " link Usage 68} option shouldn't give much trouble, but just be aware of what
it does. Setting it very high will result in some long waits if you put a
really knackered disk in. Setting it very low (i.e. to zero) will cause
perfecly innocent mis-reads of a track to be flagged as physical disk
errors, giving the occasional read/write error requester, and sometimes
causing a newly-inserted disk to appear as DFx:????. Just ignore these
occurrences, or better still, set the retry value a bit higher (system
default is 10).
@endnode

@node Timings "Calculating Timings"

 Calculating Timings
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
(Technical details, if you wish to calculate timings for your drives.)

 Amiga drives are all supposed to conform to and work with the following
delays:

  Head stepping delay (STEP): 3 milliseconds
  Head settle delay (SETTLE): 15ms
 Calibrate delay (CALIBRATE): 4ms

 However, trackdisk uses values which err somewhat on the side of caution,
even for standard drives, and other drives may support much shorter delays,
so you can always shorten the delays, provided you use drives which are
withing Amiga specifications.

 The values given to STEP, SETTLE and CALIBRATE are in the units trackdisk
uses. Very roughly, one unit corresponds to about one MICROsecond. In fact,
one unit is one tick of the system 'E' clock. On PAL machines, this runs at
709.379 KHz, and on NTSC, 715.909 KHz. This is fixed for your machine:
nothing can change it in software. So, to calculate delay values on a PAL
machine:
  Delay value = Actual time in seconds * 709379

On NTSC machines:
  Delay value = Actual time in seconds * 715909

So, on a PAL machine:
  Standard STEP value is: 0.003 * 709379 = @{b}2129@{ub}
               SETTLE is: 0.015 * 709379 = @{b}10641@{ub}
     ...and CALIBRATE is: 0.004 * 709379 = @{b}2838@{ub}
  (I use these values myself without problems.)

On NTSC machines, they work out to: STEP = 2148
                                  SETTLE = 10739
                               CALIBRATE = 2863

 As you can see, even on an NTSC machine, the trackdisk default values are a
little excessive :).

 If you have technical details of your own drive, you can work out the
correct delays using the above method.
@endnode

